sentence: The Dow chalked up gains this week, primarily guided by economic data.
Stocks ended higher on Monday after dismal housing data pushed back the possibility of rate hike in near term.
The Dow gained on Tuesday, powered by bullish housing data.
Stocks ended mixed on Wednesday after Fed minutes showed officials looked past a June rate hike amid slow economic growth.
The Dow increased only marginally on Thursday following mixed economic data.
The Dow has gained 0.1% during the first four trading days.
Last Friday, the Dow gained 0.1% amid discouraging economic data.
A flurry of weaker-than-expected economic reports increased expectations that the Fed will refrain from raising interest rates in the near term.
Industrial production slipped 0.3% in April, marking its fifth consecutive decline.
Moreover, manufacturing output was flat in April.
Excluding autos, manufacturing output fell 0.1%.
Additionally, the Empire State Manufacturing Survey Index came in at 3.1 in May, increasing from a negative 1.19 in April.
However, the reading fell short of the consensus estimate of an uptrend to 5.85.
For the week, the blue-chip gained 0.5%.
Benchmarks ended in the green for the week amid mixed economic data, giving no clear indication to investors on the timing of a rate hike.
While industrial production, producer price index and consumer sentiment declined, claims for unemployment benefits touched a 15-year low.
Meanwhile, drop in global bond yields helped benchmarks settle in the green.
European Central Bank President Mario Draghi's commitment to continue its asset purchasing program to stimulate Eurozone's economy helped stocks recover while bond yields declined.
Additionally, a weaker dollar boosted investor sentiment on Thursday as it increases profit margins of U.S. exporters by making their products cheaper.
Stocks ended higher on Monday after dismal housing data pushed back the possibility of rate hike in near term.
The NAHB/Wells Fargo Housing Market index dropped from 56 in April to 54 in May.
The figure was in contrast to analysts' expectations that the index would increase to 57.
Additionally, Fed Chicago President Charles Evans also recommended that the Fed should hold back from hiking interest rates until 2016.
Evans finds no compelling reason to tighten financial conditions as he believes inflation is unlikely to touch Fed's target rate of 2% until 2018.
Meanwhile, Greek two-year sovereign bond yields moved north following investor concerns that the country may not be able to repay its debt to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) next month.
Spain and Italy's bond yields also soared more than 7%, while German bund yield increased 3%.
In the U.S., benchmark U.S. 10-year Treasury note yields briefly climbed to 2.23% and the 30-year Treasury note yields went up as high as 3.03%.
However, investors ignored these developments, which helped markets settle in positive territory.
The blue-chip gained 0.1%.
The Dow gained 0.1% on Tuesday, closing at a record level for the second consecutive session.
Privately-owned housing starts surged 20.2% to 1,135,000 in April from March's revised tally of 944,000.
Construction on new homes climbed at the fastest pace in April since late 2007, banking on rise in single-family housing starts.
The pace of permits for single-family homes also hit the fastest rate since early 2008.

While encouraging housing data led some investors to believe that the economy may be gaining momentum from a slow first quarter, others were concerned as to what effect this report will have on the Federal Reserve's interest rate policy.
Bond prices declined following promising housing starts report, pushing yields higher.
Stocks ended mixed on Wednesday after Fed minutes showed officials looked past a June rate hike amid slow economic growth.
Minutes from the FOMC Apr 28-29 meeting showed that officials believe a rate hike in June is "unlikely" as they remained concerned about weak economic growth in the first quarter.
They want to wait to see further improvement in labor market conditions and inflation touching its target rate of 2%.
Fed officials believed "transitory" factors were affecting the economy.
While housing numbers and employment growth picked up in April, industrial production, producer price index, consumer sentiment and retail sales numbers were discouraging.
However, the Fed minutes also stated hiking federal funds rates isn't completely off the table.
Few officials believe they had enough confidence to increase interest rates from near zero levels at the June 16-17 meeting.
The blue-chip index declined almost 0.2%.
The Dow increased only marginally on Thursday following mixed economic data.
Existing home sales declined 3.3%, coming in below consensus estimates.
Treasury yields ended lower due to discouraging existing home sales numbers.
The Philadelphia Federal Reserve's manufacturing index fell to 6.7 in May from a 7.5 in April.
Additionally, Markit's flash manufacturing purchasing managers index dropped to 53.8 in May from 54.1 in April.
However, the Conference Board's leading economic index increased 0.7% in April after it rose a 0.4% in March.
Separately, jobless claims increased for the week ending May 16.
However, the 4-week moving average declined.
The day's mostly weaker-than-expected data increased expectations that the Federal Reserve may delay hiking interest rates in the near term.

Wal-Mart Stores Inc. 's WMT fiscal first quarter 2016 earnings of $1.03 per share were within management's guidance range of 95 cents to $1.10 per share but declined 6.4% from the year-ago earnings from continuing operations of $1.10 per share.
Though the company reported positive comps at Wal-Mart U.S., a decline in sales at Sam's Club and the international business and lower operating income led to the decline in earnings.
Currency also negatively impacted earnings by 3 cents.
Total revenue of the retailer missed the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $116.3 billion and declined 0.1% to $114.8 billion (including membership and other income).
Currency depleted sales by approximately $3.28 billion.
The year-over-year decline in sales was due to soft sales at Sam's Club and the International business, which more than offset the improved comps at Wal-Mart U.S. and strong e-commerce growth.
On a constant currency basis, revenues increased 2.7% to $118.1 billion.
E-commerce sales, however, increased approximately 17% globally.

The Home Depot Inc.HD reported better-than-expected first-quarter results that benefited from a favorable spring season across most parts of the country and continued recovery in the U.S. housing market.
The company posted first-quarter fiscal 2015 adjusted earnings of $1.16 per share, up 16% year on year and beat the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $1.15.
Including one-time items, quarterly earnings surged 21% year over year to $1.21 per share.
Net sales advanced 6.1% to $20,891 million from $19,687 million in the year-ago quarter, beating the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $20,775 million.
The company's overall comparable-store sales (comps) increased 6.1% while comps in the U.S. stores grew 7.1%.
Boeing Co.BA won a big order from a Chinese consortium for its single-aisle 737 Max jets, thanks to the booming travel industry in China.

Chinese carrier Ruili Airlines and two leasing companies − AVIC International Leasing Co Ltd and Minsheng Financial Leasing Co Ltd − have signed a deal with the aerospace behemoth for 60 narrow-bodied 737 Max models.
The transaction is worth more than $6.1 billion (or 38 billion yuan).
However, the delivery schedule has not yet been disclosed.
The ordered models comprise 737 MAX 7, 8 and 9.
United Technologies Corp.UTX announced the successful pricing of its senior note offering worth €750 million ($854.4 million) in aggregate principal amount, maturing on May 22, 2023.
The notes bear an interest rate of 1.25%.
The offering will close on May 22, 2015, subject to the satisfaction of customary closing conditions.
Net proceeds generated from the 8-year note issuance will be employed toward retirement of the conglomerate's floating rate notes, which will mature this year, and for general corporate purposes.
JPMorgan Chase & Co.JPM has announced a dividend hike of 10%.
This was part of the company's 2015 capital plan that was approved by the Federal Reserve in Mar 2015.
JPMorgan will pay quarterly cash dividend of 44 cents per share.
The dividend will be paid on Jul 31 to shareholders of record as on Jul 6.
This reflects a dividend yield of 2.70%.
JPMorgan's 2015 capital plan also includes share repurchase of up to $6.4 billion starting from Apr 1, 2015 to Jun 30, 2016.
Moreover, this program includes shares repurchased to offset issuances under the company's equity-based compensation plans.

General Electric Co.GE unit GE Aviation and industrial goods manufacturer Woodward, Inc. (WWD) recently entered into a joint venture with an equal stake to enhance fuel systems for General Electric's large commercial aircraft engine lines.
Per the agreement, Woodward will receive $250 million in cash.
The transaction is expected to close by the end of 2015.
In a separate development, GE recently announced the launch of its digital wind farm to address a long-standing need for greater flexibility in renewable power.
The digital wind farm is a new wind ecosystem that is likely to boost the operating efficiency of a wind farm.
The digital farm concept essentially combines General Electric's world-class turbines with interconnected digital technology, also known as the Industrial Internet.
The table given below shows the price movements of the 10 largest components of the Dow, which is a price weighted index, over the last five days and during the last six months.
Over the last five trading days, the Dow has gained 0.5%.
Overall, stocks experienced gains this week.
Economic data dominated proceedings and had a mixed impact on proceedings.
While positive reports reflected economic growth, they also led to heightened concerns that a rate hike was in the offing.
However, dismal data from several fronts and comments from Fed officials indicate that any action in this direction may be some time away.
Meanwhile, international developments have had a negligible impact on the direction of stocks.
Several economic reports are scheduled for release next week.
This includes data on housing, durable orders, consumer confidence and all-important GDP data.
Following the end of the earnings season, it is likely that these reports will influence market direction going forward.
